  "prompt": "How many types of metadata are there?",
  "response": "There are generally four main types of metadata:\n\n1. Descriptive Metadata\n- Describes and identifies information resources\n- Includes titles, authors, dates, keywords\n- Helps in searching and identifying items\n\n2. Structural Metadata\n- Explains how different parts of a resource are organized\n- Defines relationships between components\n- Used in complex digital objects like multi-page documents\n\n3. Administrative Metadata\n- Provides information about technical management of resources\n- Includes creation date, file type, access permissions\n- Helps in managing and preserving digital assets\n\n4. Technical Metadata\n- Contains technical information about digital files\n- Includes file format, size, creation software\n- Useful for preservation and technical management\n\nSome sources might also mention additional subtypes or variations, but these four are the most commonly recognized types of metadata across different domains like library science, digital archives, and information management.\n\nEach type serves a specific purpose in organizing, identifying, and managing information resources effectively.",
